===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|emeraude|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|esmeraude|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|VL.}} ''*esmaralda, *esmaraldus'', variant of {{etyl|la}} {{term|smaragdus|lang=la}},, from {{etyl|grc}} {{l|grc|σμάραγδος}}, {{term|μάραγδος|lang=grc|tr=maragdos}}, from Semitic root ''b-r-q'' “to shoot lightning, to flash in darkness”, compare {{etyl|he}} {{term|בָּרֶקֶת|tr=bareket|lang=he}} “emerald, flashing gem”, Akkadian ''barruktu'', Arabic ''buraq'' “lightning”.

{{etyl|sa}} {{term|मरकत|sc=Deva|tr=marakata}} from a Semitic language.

Persian {{term|زمرد|lang=fa|tr=zomorrod}} (whence Turkish {{term|zümrüt|lang=tr}}, whence Russian {{term|изумруд|lang=ru|tr=izumrud}} from Ancient Greek {{term|σμάραγδος|lang=grc|tr=smaragdos}}.

